screen_name: The last day of symptoms, the fever was gone, but I had a terrible, terrible migraine. One of the worst I've had. My neck hurt, and the back of my head was throbbing. I was also coughing and nauseous, and I vomited most of the soup I'd eaten. A cold shower and sleep helped.

After around two and a half days of those symptoms (which were the most intense period), the fever started going down, although I still felt exhausted. The coughing fits stopped. Hydration was the most helpful thing to make me feel better. But my head and neck kept hurting.

About three and a half days in, I developed a fever (101.5 F). I had barely any appetite, and I had started coughing. I had a neck and back ache, and still felt tired. The coughing wasn't consistent - it came in fits (once a day) and I coughed up a little phlegm.

The last day of symptoms, the fever was gone, but I had a terrible, terrible migraine. One of the worst I've had. My neck hurt, and the back of my head was throbbing. I was also coughing and nauseous, and I vomited most of the soup I'd eaten. A cold shower and sleep helped.

At this stage, water, soup, and Tylenol (acetaminophen - as recommended by the doctor) helped, in that it made the coughing stop and helped me sleep. Also lukewarm showers and baths were helpful with the body-temperature discomfort I was feeling.

Two days after the tiredness set in, my throat started feeling scratchy. My temperature started going up (still not a fever, but I definitely was feeling flashes of being either too hot or too cold). Advice I was given: Tylenol if I got a fever, and lots of fluids (like soup).

Two days after the tiredness set in, my throat started feeling scratchy. My temperature started going up (still not a fever, but I definitely was feeling flashes of being either too hot or too cold). Advice I was given: Tylenol if I got a fever, and lots of fluids (like soup).

I had already been in quarantine after known exposure to someone tested for COVID. 12 days into quarantine, I started feeling fatigued and sleepy more often, and my temperature was a little higher than normal (but not a fever). I was hydrating, but taking no specific meds yet.

Just got test results (after around 12 days of waiting) letting me know I tested positive for COVID-19. I'm feeling completely fine now and am out of isolation, but I am offering my symptoms here as a temporarily able-bodied cis woman in her late 20s for the sake of info (1)
